<li><strong>Nutrient-Rich Foods:</strong> Add easy assimilation, non-acidic and nourishing foods to the diet like soups, porridge &amp; khichdi, etc.</li>



<li><strong>Fruits and Vegetables:</strong> Take oranges, papaya, apples, spinach and carrots for vitamin needs Foods rich in fibre should also be taken regularly.</li>



<li><strong>Light and Non-Spicy Meals:</strong> Do not consume foods that are rich in fats and oils, spicy foods or foods that take time to digest.</li>



<li><strong>Probiotics:</strong> Yogurt and fermented foods contribute to the health of the digestive system and provide an immunity boost.</li>



<li><strong>Avoid Processed Foods:</strong> Avoid processed foods and foods considered junk foods as these lower the immune system of the body.</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Lifestyle Changes:</strong></p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Adequate Rest:</strong> Take adequate rest and avoid pushing the body in order to heal after an injury.</li>



<li><strong>Maintain Proper Hygiene</strong>: Avoid contact with other people or pets to reduce the chance of getting infected again.</li>



<li><strong>Lukewarm Baths:</strong> Alleviates fever and gives some relief.</li>



<li><strong>Light Physical Activity: </strong>Taking a gentle stretch or even some deep breaths will help with blood flow but should not involve sweating.</li>



<li><strong>Avoid Cold Exposure: </strong>Stay warm and do not let your exposure to hot or cold temperatures worsen the symptoms.</li>



<li><strong>Stay in a Well-Ventilated Room:</strong> Ventilation also has a major role of facilitating efficient healing time and lack of cross infection.</li>
</ul>



